import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import pmdarima as pm
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Usar solo los datos 'Real' para entrenar el modelo ARIMA
df_real = data_second_sheet[data_second_sheet['nature'] == 'Real']

# Configurar la serie temporal
df_real.set_index('date', inplace=True)
ts = df_real['Real Wage Index']

# Aplicar la transformación logarítmica y la diferenciación
ts_log = np.log(ts)
ts_log_diff = ts_log.diff().dropna()

# Crear una variable dummy para junio de 2020
df_real['dummy'] = 0
df_real.loc['2000-03-01', 'dummy'] = 1
df_real.loc['2000-06-01', 'dummy'] = 1
exog = df_real['dummy'].reindex(ts_log_diff.index).fillna(0)

# Entrenar el mejor modelo ARIMA automáticamente con exógena
model = pm.auto_arima(ts_log_diff, exogenous=exog, seasonal=False, stepwise=True, suppress_warnings=True)

# Obtener los coeficientes del modelo
coefficients = model.params()

# Predecir en el conjunto de entrenamiento
in_sample_preds_diff = model.predict_in_sample(exogenous=exog)
in_sample_preds_log = ts_log.iloc[0] + in_sample_preds_diff.cumsum()
in_sample_preds_final = np.exp(in_sample_preds_log)

# Calcular la desviación
deviation = ts[1:] - in_sample_preds_final

# Crear un DataFrame con las predicciones y las desviaciones para el conjunto de entrenamiento
in_sample_df = pd.DataFrame({
    'Actual': ts[1:],
    'Forecasted': in_sample_preds_final,
    'Deviation': deviation
})

In [24]:



     


import pandas as pd
from plotnine import ggplot, aes, geom_line, geom_point, labs, theme_minimal

# Creating the DataFrame with the provided data
data = {
    'period': range(6),
    'Forecast_with_ma': [-114.777686, 117.874277, -116.213405, 114.587557, -112.972833, 111.392484],
    'Forecast_without_ma': [-138.366636, 136.429744, -134.508344, 132.625625, -130.757636, 128.927579],
    'diff': [23.588950, 18.555467, 18.294938, 18.038067, 17.784803, 17.535095]
}

df = pd.DataFrame(data)

# Creating the plot using plotnine
plot = (
    ggplot(df, aes(x='period', y='diff')) +
    geom_line(color='blue', size=1.5) +
    geom_point(color='black', size=3) +
    labs(
        title='Difference between Forecasts with and without MA',
        x='Period',
        y='Difference'
    ) +
    theme_minimal()+
    theme(
        plot_background=element_text(color='white', fill='white'),
        panel_background=element_text(color='white', fill='white'),
        plot_title=element_text(size=12, face='bold', color='blue', ha='center'),
        axis_title_x=element_text(size=12, face='bold', color='blue'),
        axis_title_y=element_text(size=12, face='bold', color='blue'),
        legend_title=element_text(size=10, face='bold', color='blue'),
        legend_background=element_text(color='white', fill='white'),
        legend_position='top'
    )
)

# Display the plot
print(plot)



     






















    
    

















    
    

































Recap:¶
    

  • There differences are a function of the last 1 or two errors, and these are minimized since models have passed statistical tests associated with heteroscedasticity, residual plot, normality and goodness of fit
    • 

  • In the long term, these differences are negligible
    • 

  • MA coefficients are considered during the training process. Hence, AR and exogenous coefficients are enabled to change according to the MA, which means MAs are considered in the exercise
    •
